Putin as the Culprit
Moscow — Medical experts from Germany, France, and Sweden unanimously agree that Alexei Navalny was poisoned with the nerve agent Novichok. Navalny is Russia's leading opposition figure and the founder of the Anti-Corruption Foundation.
Fortunately, due to Navalny's survival, relations between Russia and Germany do not deteriorate further.
To demonstrate her "clear stance," German Chancellor Angela Merkel announced that Navalny is a "victim persecuted for exercising his freedom of speech."
In her view, this incident is very serious, and only the Russian government can, and must, respond.
She emphasized that the whole world needs an explanation.
Merkel called on Russian authorities to conduct an independent and transparent investigation.
The EU and the UK also supported this call.
If the investigation proves that the Russian government was behind the incident, the EU Commission will impose new sanctions.
No matter what, poisoning is prohibited according to the global ban on chemical weapons.
This is not the first time Putin's government has used the nerve agent Novichok against its political opponents.
In 2018, Russian double agent Sergei Skripal and his daughter Yulia were poisoned on British soil.
Both survived and went into hiding.
The Kremlin strongly denied both incidents.
Regarding Navalny's case, Kremlin spokesperson Dmitry Peskov insisted there is "no evidence to blame the Russian government."
Russian Foreign Intelligence Service Director Sergei Naryshkin even said it was the behavior of Western intelligence agencies, blaming Russia's government credibility.
Naryshkin's statement is clearly preposterous, but he also points out a fact: the Navalny case has more cons than pros for Russia.
Poisoning a prominent political rival just before the upcoming elections, and using a toxin developed during the Soviet era, is hard to justify.
In particular, this timing is more intriguing given that the neighboring Belarusian people are protesting the August election.
Moreover, the Kremlin's initial reaction to the Navalny case is especially puzzling.
In carrying out the crime, shouldn't the Russian government have planned more carefully?
If, as Germany claims, it was indeed the Russian government that carried it out, this assassination would have been a failed operation.
Putin has always been the Darth Vader of the international political arena (the chief antagonist in the Star Wars films), interfering in the U.S. elections, inciting street protests in France, luring Britain into Brexit, and supporting Syria's Bashar al-Assad.
As a former KGB officer, he is shrewd, farsighted, and cunning.
Why then could he not kill Skripal and Navalny?
Why did Navalny escape to Germany and was quickly diagnosed as having been poisoned?
Now, Putin is facing international condemnation and sanctions, and the Nord Stream 2 gas pipeline to Germany is at risk of being canceled.
This murder clearly wasn't worth it.
In fact, this has only further fueled public opposition to the Russian authorities' actions.
Even if it wasn't really done by Putin, the accusations against Western intelligence agencies are even more excessive.
If such accusations were true, German and Swedish scientists would not have revealed the nerve agent Novichok.
More likely, it stems from a conspiracy orchestrated by Putin's political inner circle.
Perhaps Putin needed Navalny to be quiet before the elections, or perhaps it was a fallout from his anti-corruption investigations.
In Russia, you can buy all sorts of products and services on the black market, including military-grade nerve agents.
Putin's political enforcers, while loyal, are very stupid; they thought poisoning Navalny was a good idea, and only a few knew the truth.
Other failed poisoning attempts share similar characteristics: the poisoning of journalists Vladimir Kara-Murza in 2015 and 2017. Kara-Murza was the coordinator of the Public Investigation Committee for Khodorkovsky.
The poisoning of Peter Verzilov, the publisher of the independent news website Mediazona, in 2018.
Mediazona is a website that reports on Russian judicial abuses.
Going back further to 2006, there was the poisoning of former FSB Alexander Litvinenko, who frequently criticized Russia's security agencies.
As with the Navalny case, such poisonings often backfire.
In 2004, Anna Politkovskaya, a columnist for the liberal newspaper Novaya Gazeta, was poisoned on a flight from Moscow to Beslan, though she survived. Two years later, she was shot dead in the elevator of her apartment building.
As Putin said, her death dealt a huge blow to the image of the Russian government.
This is not an attempt to exonerate the Kremlin.
Whether Putin personally ordered it or not, the system he created allowed such crimes to happen. This system is both ineffective and useless, a farce carried out by some shameless actors.
Navchinsky's death was what the Kremlin wanted, and the hounds' ultimate goal is to satisfy their master Putin.
In Putin's inner circle, loyalty is the only goal.
Even if the poisoning attempt fails, they will not be punished.
Because they do it for the president's benefit.
Those who want to find evidence of the poisoning might be disappointed.
Still, the Kremlin is the real culprit, regardless of this.
Western countries must clearly state that they will take sanctions on Russia even if it affects their own economy.
Putin has created a system centered around himself.
All responsibilities that arise in Russia are his own.
